article.headline: Polk's 22 points, 13 boards lead Wildcats
article.linkText: Arizona dusts Washington for share of Pac-10 title
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Arizona defeated Washington 71-54 on Saturday and
secured a tie for the Pac-10 regular season title for the first
time in the school's history.

Shawntinice Polk scored 22 points and had 13 rebounds to lead
Arizona (22-7, 14-4 Pac-10) to the win.

"Our team really wanted this championship," coach Joan
Bonvicini said. "It was one of our goals from the get-go. The
first one is the hardest to get."

Arizona ended up tied with Stanford for the regular-season title
when the No. 10 Cardinal defeated Oregon State 67-66 later
Saturday. Stanford got the top spot in the Pac-10 tournament, which
starts Friday, on a tiebreaker.

Polk, who was serenaded by Washington before she committed to
Arizona, became the only sophomore in Wildcats history to top 1,000
points as she reached 1,015 points in her 60th game.

"She's an amazing talent, everybody knows that," Washington
head coach June Daugherty said. "She has very good hands and they
can just about throw anything up and she'll come with it."

The Wildcats led by 15 points at just three minutes into the
game. Washington (16-11, 9-9 Pac-10) never got closer than six
points behind at 45-39.

Arizona used a pressure defense in the second half and was never
threatened by the Huskies.

"Our guards were awesome tonight, the press especially," Polk
said. "They gave me time to rest. While they applied pressure up
front, I just sat back and rested up and got my legs back."

Washington shot a dismal 28 percent from the field.

Arizona's win was only its second ever in Seattle. The last came
Jan. 15, 2000.

Giuliana Mendiola scored 22 points and had four assists for
Washington. A senior, she finished her career as the Huskies'
all-time leader in assists with 589 and second in scoring with
1,827 points.

"I'm upset we lost, but our team fought real, real hard,"
Mendiola said. "We just couldn't knock down shots is all."

Andrea Lalum scored 16 points for Washington, which broke a
three-game winning streak.

Dee-Dee Wheeler scored 17 points for the Wildcats. Aimee Gryzb
added 15 points and became the team's all-time leader in minutes
played with 3,722.

The Huskies played without senior Gioconda Mendiola, who was
serving a one-game suspension handed down by Washington for a
scuffle Thursday night against Kylan Loney of Arizona State.

Arizona led at the half, 34-28.

The Wildcats dominated inside, outscoring Washington 20-8 in the
paint during the first half.
